%I A396059 #27 May 20 2026 17:29:08
%S A396059 0,2,5,7,10,8,15,13,20,22,17,19,30,28,27,25,40,42,45,47,34,32,39,37,
%T A396059 60,62,57,59,54,52,51,49,80,82,85,87,90,88,95,93,68,70,65,67,78,76,75,
%U A396059 73,120,122,125,127,114,112,119,117,108,110,105,107,102,100,99,97
%N A396059 a(n) is the action of "Rule 90" elementary cellular automaton on the binary representation of n if the cells may only expand into the significant bit.
%C A396059 A048725 allows cells to expand in both directions; its example gives 101 -> 10001 (as opposed to this 101 -> 1000). This sequence does not allow the cells to expand into the least significant bit.
%C A396059 A048725 is a subsequence.
%C A396059 When calculating the LSB edge, the out-of-bounds cell is taken to be 0.
%H A396059 Mia Boudreau, <a href="/A396059/b396059.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A396059 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Rule90.html">Rule 90</a>.
%H A396059 The Wolfram Atlas of Simple Programs, <a href="https://atlas.wolfram.com/01/01/90/">Rule 90</a>.
%F A396059 a(n) = (2*n) XOR floor(n/2).
%F A396059 a(n) = Sum_{i=0..floor(log_2(n)+1)} 2^i * b(90, 4*b(n,i+1) + 2*b(n,i) + b(n,i-1)), where b(n,i) = floor(n/(2^i)) mod 2.
%F A396059 a(2*n) = A048725(n).
%e A396059 for a(5): 101 -> 1000, so a(5) = 8.
%e A396059 for a(10): 1010 -> 10001, so a(10) = A048725(5) = 17.
%t A396059 A396059[n_] := BitXor[2*n, Quotient[n, 2]]; Array[A396059, 100, 0] (* _Paolo Xausa_, May 20 2026 *)
%o A396059 (C) unsigned long long a(unsigned long long n){return (n<<1)^(n>>1);}
%Y A396059 Cf. A048725.
%K A396059 nonn,base,easy
%O A396059 0,2
%A A396059 _Mia Boudreau_, May 15 2026
